[[Image:Bayerischer wald1.jpg|thumb|300px|Results of [[bark beetle]] in the Bavarian Forest]] [[image:Zell-bayerischer-wald.jpg|thumb|The village of Zell in the Bavarian Forest]] [[File:Arber-Gipfelregion.jpg|thumb|Summit of the Großer Arber with its [[summit cross]] and radome]] The '''Bavarian Forest''' ([[German language|German]]: ''{{Audio|De-Bayerischer_Wald.ogg|Bayerischer Wald}}'') is a wooded low-mountain region in [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]]. It extends along the [[Czech Republic|Czech]] border and is continued on the Czech side by the [[Bohemian Forest|Šumava]] (Bohemian Forest). Geographically the Bavarian Forest and Bohemian Forest are sections of the same mountain range. A part of the Bavarian Forest belongs to the '''Bavarian Forest National Park''' (''Nationalpark Bayerischer Wald'') (240&nbsp;km²), established in 1970 as the first national park in Germany. Another 3,008&nbsp;km² belong to the [[Bavarian Forest Nature Park]] (''Naturpark Bayerischer Wald''), established 1967, and 1738&nbsp;km² to the [[Eastern Bavarian Forest Nature Park]] (''Naturpark Oberer Bayerischer Wald''), established 1965. The Bavarian Forest is a remnant of the [[Hercynian Forest]] that stretched across southern [[Germania]] in Roman times. It is the largest protected forest area in central Europe.<ref>{{cite |url=http://www.stripes.com/article.asp?section=103&article=67056 |title=Bavarian Forest delights with nature’s elegant artistry}}</ref>
The highest mountain in the region is the [[Großer Arber]] ("Great Arber", 1,456&nbsp;m). The main river is the [[Regen river|Regen]], which is formed by the conjunction of White Regen and Black Regen and leaves the mountains towards the city of [[Regensburg]].
== Places of interest == Amongst the places of interest in the Bavarian Forest are: {| |- valign="top" | style="padding-right:2em;" | * National Park Information Centre in [[Neuschönau]] * National Park Information Centre in [[Ludwigsthal (Lindberg)|Ludwigsthal]] Nature * The [[Pfahl (Bavarian Forest)|Pfahl]], a 150 km long rock formation * [[Teufelstisch (Bavarian Forest)|Teufelstisch]] ("Devil's Table") near [[Bischofsmais]] * [[Buchberger Leite]] between [[Freyung, Bavaria|Freyung]] and [[Ringelai]] * [[Höllbachgspreng]] on the [[Großer Falkenstein]] * The [[Schachten]], former pasture land in the national park, between the Falkenstein and the Rachel * Saußbach Gorge near [[Waldkirchen]] * Valley of the [[Ilz (river)|Ilz]] * [[Kleiner Arbersee|Kleiner]] and [[Großer Arbersee]] lakes * Wildlife park in Ludwigsthal * Bavarian Forest Animal Park in [[Lohberg (Bavaria)|Lohberg]] * Open-air animal park near [[Neuschönau]] * [[Frauenau Dam]] Observation towers * [[Canopy walkway]] in the [[Bavarian Forest National Park]] near [[Neuschönau]] | Culture * Gabreta Celtic village near [[Ringelai]] * [[Bavarian Forest Museum Village]] by the [[Dreiburgensee]] lake * [[Lower Bavarian Open-Air Museums|Finsterau Open-Air Museum]] * [[Weißenstein Castle (Lower Bavaria)|Weißenstein Castle]] ruins near [[Regen]] with the "Glass Forest" (''Gläserner Wald'') * Hunting and Fishing Museum at [[Wolfstein Castle]] in [[Freyung, Bavaria|Freyung]] * Agricultural Museum in Regen * [[Zwiesel Forest Museum|Forest Museum]] in [[Zwiesel]] * [[Frauenau Glass Museum]] in [[Frauenau]] * [[Mariä Himmelfahrt (Frauenau)|Maria Himmelfahrt Church]] in Frauenau * Wolfstein Gallery in Freyung * ''Fürstenzeche'' Historic Silver and Fluospar mine in [[Lam]] * Mine on the [[Silberberg (Bodenmais)|Silberberg]] near [[Bodenmais]] * Baptist Kitzlinger Ski Jumps in [[Breitenberg]] * Church of the Sacred Heart in [[Ludwigsthal (Lindberg)]] * Former abbey church at [[Rinchnach]] |}
